Autorregressive models

In an autoregression model, the variable of interest is forecast using a linear combination of past values of the variable. The term autoregression indicates that it is a regression of the variable against itself.

These models are based on the idea that crrent values of the series depend on previous values of the same series.

An autoregressive model of order p \(AR(p)\) has the form:

\[\begin{align*} y_{t} = c + \phi_{1}y_{t-1} + \phi_{2}y_{t-2} + \dots + \phi_{p}y_{t-p} + \varepsilon_{t} \end{align*}\]
  • \(\varepsilon_t\) is white noise
  • \(y_{t}\) is stationary

Shifting terms to the left and using backshift notation, we may express these model as:

\[ y_t - \phi_1 y_{t-1} - \phi_2 y_{t-2} - \dots+ \phi_p y_{t-p} = \varepsilon_t \]

\[ (1-\phi_1\,B-\phi_2\,B^2-\dots-\phi_p\,B^p)y_t = \varepsilon_t \]

\[ \left(1-\sum_{i=1}^p\phi_iB^i\right)y_t = \varepsilon_t \]

Or, using the definition of the autoregressive operator:

\[ \phi(B)=1-\phi_1\,B-\phi_2\,B^2-\dots-\phi_p\,B^p = \left(1-\sum_{i=1}^p\phi_iB^i\right) \]

The model might be simply expressed as:

\[ \phi(B)y_t=\varepsilon_t \]

Restrictions on the coefficients

Note that the model is a regression of random components. The predictors (the lagged values of \(y_t\)) are random, whereas in normal regression we assumed that the predictors were not random variables. This will give rise to some technical difficulties, most notably the need to impose some restrictions on the parameters of the autoregressive model, whereas no restrictions applied in normal regression.

Deriving the restrictions for the parameters can be complex and is not necessary for practical purposes when fitting models with statistical packages such as fable, since this software already takes care of the matter. The reader is referred to chapter 4 of reference [2] and chapter 3 of reference [3] for a more detailed derivation. Here we give the constraints for \(AR(1)\) and \(AR(2)\) models:

  • For an \(AR(1)\) model: \(-1 < \phi_1 < 1\).
  • For an \(AR(2)\) model, we already have three constraints:
    • \(-1 < \phi_2 < 1\)
    • \(\phi_1+\phi_2 < 1\)
    • \(\phi_2-\phi_1 < 1\)
  • For an \(AR(3)\), the restrictions are much more complicated.

These restrictions ensure that the autoregressive models remain stationary.

The equation for an AR(1) model is:

\[\begin{align*} y_{t} = c + \phi_{1}y_{t-1} + \varepsilon_{t} \end{align*}\]
  • when \(\phi_1 = 1\) and \(c = 0\), the restrictions on the parameters are not satisfied and we end up with a random walk model, which is not stationary.
  • when \(\phi_1 = 1\) and \(c \neq 0\) the restrictions on the parameters are not satisfied and we end up with a random walk with drift model, which is not stationary.
  • when \(\phi_1 = 0\) and \(c = 0\), the model is equivalent to white noise.
  • when \(\phi_1 < 0\), \(y_t\) tends to oscillate around the mean.

Autoregressive models are very flexible for handling a wide range of time series patterns, and in an ARIMA context they are restricted to handle only stationary series. Below some examples on the aspect of autoregressive models that satisfy the parameter restrictions:

  • In both cases \(\varepsilon_t \sim N(0, 1)\). Changing the variance of this term will only change the variance of the series, not the patterns.

  • Changing the \(\phi_k\) parameters (within their constraints) generates different time series patterns.

  • AR(1) in figure has equation \(y_t = 18 - 0.8y_{t-1} + \varepsilon_t\)

  • AR(2) in figure has equation \(y_t = 8 + 1.3y_{t-1} - 0.7y_{t-2} + \varepsilon_t\)

Moving Average models

Consider a white noise series \(\varepsilon_t\) and think of \(\varepsilon_t\) as a âshockâ to the process at time \(t\). A moving average model considers the forecast variable as a regression on that shock and its past values:

\[\begin{align*} y_{t} = c + \varepsilon_t + \theta_{1}\varepsilon_{t-1} + \theta_{2}\varepsilon_{t-2} + \dots + \theta_{q}\varepsilon_{t-q}, \end{align*}\]

The name moving average comes because \(y_t\) can be though as a weighted moving average of the past few âshocksâ, although the coefficients of the regression rarely add up to one, as they would in a moving average. Do not confuse moving average models with the moving average smoothing discussed in time series decomposition.

  • Moving average process used for forecasting
  • Moving average smoothing used to estimate trend-cycle of past values

A case of particular interest is to consider the shocks \(\varepsilon_t\) as forecast errors. That is, to predict \(y_t\) as a regression on previous forecast errors. Since independence does not hold in general for time series, this is a good way of modelling possible relationships between the errors of the few forecast values. Of course, we do not observe the values of \(\varepsilon_t\), so it is not really a regression in the usual sense.

Unlike the autoregressive process, the moving average process is stationary for any value of the parameters. Below some examples of Moving Average processes:

  • In both cases \(\varepsilon_t \sim N(0, 1)\). Changing the variance of this term will only change the variance of the series, not the patterns.

  • Changing the \(\theta_k\) parameters (within their constraints) generates different time series patterns.

  • MA(1): \(y_t = 20 + \varepsilon_t + 0.8\varepsilon_{t-1}\)

  • MA(2): \(y_t = \varepsilon_t - \varepsilon_{t-1} + 0.8\varepsilon_{t-2}\)

Causality and autoregressive models - Autoregressive related to MA.

Stationary \(AR(p)\) models can be written as an \(MA(\infty)\) model. That is the reason we want them to remain stationary in an ARIMA context.

As an example:

\[\begin{align*} y_t &= \phi_1y_{t-1} + \varepsilon_t\\ &= \phi_1(\phi_1y_{t-2} + \varepsilon_{t-1}) + \varepsilon_t\\ &= \phi_1^2y_{t-2} + \phi_1 \varepsilon_{t-1} + \varepsilon_t\\ &= \phi_1^3y_{t-3} + \phi_1^2\varepsilon_{t-2} + \phi_1 \varepsilon_{t-1} + \varepsilon_t\\ &\text{etc.} \end{align*}\]

If the constraint \(-1 < \phi_1 < 1\) is satisfied, the value \(\phi_{1}^k\) decreases as \(k\) increases:

\[\begin{align*} y_t = \varepsilon_t + \phi_1 \varepsilon_{t-1} + \phi_1^2 \varepsilon_{t-2} + \phi_1^3 \varepsilon_{t-3} + \cdots, \end{align*}\]

The term âcausalityâ is used to signal that \(y_t\) depends only on past values of the shocks.

Invertibility

If certain constraints are imposed on the MA parameters then we can ensure that the model is invertible, i.e.Â the \(MA(q)\) process can be expressed as an \(AR(\infty)\) process.

This invertibility constraints are similar to the stationary constraints for \(AR(p)\) processes:

  • For an \(MA(1)\) model: \(-1<\theta_1<1\)
  • For an \(MA(2)\) model:
    • \(-1<\theta_1<1\)
    • \(\theta_2+\theta_1 >-1\)
    • \(\theta_1 -\theta_2 < 1\)
  • For \(q \geq 3\) the constraints get more complex, but they will be handled automatically by the fable package.

For a detaild derivation of these conditions the reader is referred to references [2] and [3].

Invertible models are useful for their mathematical properties. Consider the MA(1) process \(y_t = \varepsilon_t + \theta_1\varepsilon_{t-1}\). The \(AR(\infty)\) representation is interesting because it enables to writte the most recent âshockâ or âerrorâ as a linear function of the current and past observations:

\[\begin{align*} \varepsilon_t = \sum_{j=0}^\infty (-\theta_1)^j y_{t-j}. \end{align*}\]

This is used in ARIMA models to estimate the values of the errors and past errors from the observations.

ARMA models

Combining \(AR(p)\) and \(MA(q)\) processes we can produce \(ARMA(p,q)\) processes. These are very flexible for handling stationary time series, with the

  • autoregressive part being able to capture a wide range of time series patterns
  • moving average part including the lagged errors as regressors.
\[\begin{equation} y_{t} = c + \phi_{1}y_{t-1} + \cdots + \phi_{p}y_{t-p} + \theta_{1}\varepsilon_{t-1} + \cdots + \theta_{q}\varepsilon_{t-q} + \varepsilon_{t} \end{equation}\]

When we start combining models in this manner, it is useful to use the backshift notation:

\[\begin{equation} \tag{9.2} \begin{array}{c c c c} (1-\phi_1B - \cdots - \phi_p B^p)y_t = &c + (1 + \theta_1 B + \cdots + \theta_q B^q)\varepsilon_t\\ {\uparrow} & {\uparrow}\\ \text{AR($p$)} & \text{MA($q$)}\\ \end{array} \end{equation}\]

ARMA(p, q) Models and stationary processes:

These statements are proved in references 2 and 3.

  • The Wold decomposition shows that any stationary time series may be represented as a linear combination of white noise.
  • On the other hand it can be shown that any ARMA model can be expressed in a form that is a linear combination of white noise.

As a consequence, ARMA models are capable of modelling stationary time series.

Selecting appropriate valeues for p and q can be difficult. We will use two approaches:

  • Inspecting the Autocorrelation (ACF) and Partial Autocorrelation (PACF) diagrams of the stationary process. This will let us infer appropriate values for \(p\) and \(q\) and later try a few more models around these values

  • Using the automatic search in the ARIMA() function from the fable() package, which looks for values of \(p\) and \(q\) does this for you automatically.

Example: Egyptian Exports

eg_exports <- global_economy %>%
  filter(Code == "EGY")

eg_exports %>%
  autoplot(Exports) +
  labs(y = "% of GDP", title = "Egyptian exports")

Let us test for stationarity:

eg_exports %>%
  features(Exports, unitroot_kpss)
# A tibble: 1 x 3
  Country          kpss_stat kpss_pvalue
  <fct>                <dbl>       <dbl>
1 Egypt, Arab Rep.     0.192         0.1

The series above is stationary (remember that cyclicity can be part of stationary time series), making it appropriate for an ARMA model.

The following code fits a non-seasonal ARIMA model (see next class) automatically. In this case \(d=0\) will be selected (no differencing required since the model is stationary) and therefore the model will be an ARMA model:

fit <- global_economy %>%
  filter(Code == "EGY") %>%
  model(ARIMA(Exports))

report(fit)
Series: Exports 
Model: ARIMA(2,0,1) w/ mean 

Coefficients:
         ar1      ar2      ma1  constant
      1.6764  -0.8034  -0.6896    2.5623
s.e.  0.1111   0.0928   0.1492    0.1161

sigma^2 estimated as 8.046:  log likelihood=-141.57
AIC=293.13   AICc=294.29   BIC=303.43

We can see that two autoregressive terms and one moving average term have been included. On the other hand, the 0 in ARIMA(2, 0, 1) meand that no order differencing has been deemed appropriate (which makes sense, since the data is already stationary). Specifics on the notation ARIMA(p, d, q) will be given later:

The resulting model is:

\[\begin{align*} y_t = 2.56 + 1.68 y_{t-1} - 0.80 y_{t-2} - 0.69 \varepsilon_{t-1} + \varepsilon_{t} \end{align*}\]

where \(\varepsilon_t\) is white noise with a standard deviation of \(\sqrt(8.046) = 2.837\), has can be seen in the report.

fit %>% forecast(h=10) %>%
  autoplot(global_economy) +
  geom_line(data = augment(fit),
          aes(y = .fitted), col = "red"
          ) +
  labs(y = "% of GDP", title = "Egyptian exports")

ACF and PACF plots - relation with \(p\) and \(q\)

It is sometimes possible to use the ACF and PACF plots to determine the appropriate values for \(p\) and \(q\).

The plots must be generated for the stationary data, since it is this data that can be modelled using an ARMA process.

When inspecting the plots, the following table (ref 2. and 3.) can be used to determine the orders:

AR(p) MA(q) ARMA(p,q)
ACF Tails-off Cuts off after lag q Tails-off
PACF Cuts-off after lag p Tails off Tails-off

It can be shown that it is not possible for both the ACF and PACF of an ARMA process to both cut-off. In this table: * tails-off means that the function is exponentially decaying or sinusoidally decaying. * cuts-off means that there are no relevant autocorrelation coefficients beyond lag p (or q).

ACF

Shows the autocorrelations which measure the relationship between \(y_t\) and \(y_{t-k}\) for different values of k

  • if \(y_t\) and \(y_{t-1}\) are correlated, \(y_{y-1}\) and \(y_{t-2}\) are also correlated
  • \(y_t\) and \(y_{t-2}\) might be correlated simply because they are both connected yo \(y_{t-1}\) rather than due to information contained in \(y_{t-2}\) that could be useful to focast \(y_t\)
eg_exports %>%
  ACF(Exports) %>%
  autoplot()

PACF - Partial Autocorrelation Function

  • Partial autocorrelation

Many times we want to find the correlation between two variables but removing the effect of other variables. This is known as partial autocorrelation.

In the case of a time series \(\{y_t\}\), it corresponds to finding the autocorrelation between variables \((y_t, y_{t-k})\) while removing the effect of all the lags in-between them: \(y_{t-1}, t_{t-2},\dots , y_{t-k+1}\).

In more general terms, if we had three variables \(x\), \(y\) and \(z\), the partial autocorrelation between \(x\) and \(y\) would be the correlation between \(x\) and \(y\) having removed any effect derived from the fact that both \(x\) and \(y\) might be correlated to \(z\). We write this function as:

\[ \rho_{xy|z}=corr\{x-\hat x, y-\hat y\} \]

where we imply that we want to find the correlation between \(x\) and \(y\) while removing the effect of \(z\).

There is an easy interpretation of partial autocorrelation in terms of the coefficients of a linear regression model. Think of the following two models:

\[ y_t = \beta_0 + \beta_1z \]

\[ y_t = \beta_0+\beta_1x+\beta_2z \]

In the first model, \(\beta_1\) can be interpreted as the linear dependency between y and z. In the second model, \(\beta_2\) would be interpreted as the linear dependency between \(y\) and \(z\) with the linear dependency between \(x\) and \(y\) already accounted for.

In the case of time series, we could fit an autoregression model (a regression of the series \(y_t\) on its lagged values) and perform a similar interpretation. Consider the following two models:

\[ y_t = \beta_0 + \phi_1y_{t-3} \]

\[ y_t = \beta_0+\phi_1y_{t-1}+\phi_2y_{t-2}+\phi_3y_{t-3} \]

In the first model, \(\phi_1\) can be interpreted as the linear dependency between \(y\) and \(y_{t-3}\). In the second model, \(\phi_3\) would be interpreted as the linear dependency between \(y\) and \(y_{t-3}\) with the linear dependency between \(y\) and \(y_{t-1}\) and \(y_{t-2}\) already accounted for.

Following this line of reasoning, it is clear that the first autocorrelation coefficient is equal to the first partial autocorrelation coefficient, because there are no lags in between \(y_t\) and \(y_{t-1}\).

In the example above, one possible algorithm to obtain the value of \(\phi_3\) would be the following:

  1. Fit the model \(\hat{y_t} = ay_{t-1}+by_{t-2}\)
  2. Fit the model \(\hat{y_{t-3}} = cy_{t-1}+dy_{t-2}\)
  3. Compute the residuals of the model fitted in step 1: \(y_t - \hat{y_t}\)
  4. Compute the residuals of the model fitted in step 2: \(y_{t-3} - \hat{y_{t-3}}\)
  5. Compute the correlation coefficient between the residuals of step 3 and the residuals of step 4.

Basically we are correlating \(y_t\) and \(y_{t-3}\) having removed their linear dependency with \(y_{t-1}\) and \(y_{t-2}\).

In practice there are more efficient algorithms for computing the partial autocorrelations than fitting all of these autoregressions, but they all lead to the same results.

Lets compute the PACF for the egyptian exports using the function PACF

eg_exports %>%
  filter(Code == "EGY") %>%
  PACF(Exports) %>% 
  autoplot()

PACF and ACF graphs of egyption exports

global_economy %>%
  filter(Code == "EGY") %>%
  select(Exports) %>% 
  gg_tsdisplay(plot_type = "partial")
Plot variable not specified, automatically selected `y = Exports`

In this case both functions are tailing off. If this is the situation \(p\) and \(q\) cannot be directly inferred from the graphs.
